%S A397439 1,4,9,18,36,72,144,288,576,1152,2304,4608,9216,18432,36864,73728,
%T A397439 147456,294912,589824,1179648,2359296,4718592,9437184,18874368,
%U A397439 37748736,75497472,150994944,301989888,603979776,1207959552,2415919104,4831838208,9663676416
%N A397439 Growth function of the reflection group of a three-dimensional orthoscheme with distinct edge lengths.
%C A397439 A three-dimensional orthoscheme (path simplex) is a simplex with vertices V_0, V_1, V_2, V_3 whose edges V_0V_1, V_1V_2, V_2V_3 are mutually perpendicular; here the three edge lengths are distinct positive rationals. W is the group generated by the reflections in the four facets, and a(n) is the number of elements of W of word-length n in these reflections.
%C A397439 Two facets are perpendicular exactly when they are non-consecutive, so W is the right-angled Coxeter group with the path Coxeter diagram P_4; its growth series is given by Steinberg's formula, which yields the generating function and recurrence below.
%C A397439 The growth depends only on the perpendicularity pattern, not on the edge lengths. For dimension >= 3 the geometric orbit count equals this abstract growth for any distinct edge lengths (proved in the linked paper, using that distinct lengths force the consecutive dihedral angles irrational). The 2-dimensional analog is the right-triangle reflection group A396406. Verified by direct rational-arithmetic computation on edge lengths (2,3,5).
%H A397439 Vico Bonfioli, <a href="https://github.com/ElVec1o/pythagorean-reflection-sequence">The Universal Right-Triangle Reflection Sequence (Unequal Legs)</a>, GitHub repository, 2026.
%H A397439 Vico Bonfioli, <a href="https://github.com/ElVec1o/pythagorean-reflection-sequence/blob/main/paper/journal/paper1b.pdf">Growth of n-dimensional orthoscheme reflection groups</a>, 2026.
%H A397439 Vico Bonfioli, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.20370090">Data and proofs (Zenodo)</a>, doi:10.5281/zenodo.20370090, 2026.
%H A397439 <a href="/index/Rec#order_01">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (2).
%F A397439 G.f.: (1 + x)^2 / (1 - 2*x).
%F A397439 a(0)=1, a(1)=4, a(2)=9; a(n) = 2*a(n-1) for n >= 3, so a(n) = 9*2^(n-2) for n >= 2.
%F A397439 a(n+1)/a(n) -> 2 = 1 + 2*cos(2*Pi/6).
%e A397439 a(1) = 4: the four reflections in the bounding facets are the 4 elements of word-length 1.
%t A397439 CoefficientList[Series[(1 + x)^2/(1 - 2 x), {x, 0, 32}], x]
%o A397439 (Python)
%o A397439 def aseq(N):
%o A397439     s = [1, 4, 9]
%o A397439     while len(s) < N:
%o A397439         s.append(2*s[-1])
%o A397439     return s
%o A397439 print(aseq(33))
%Y A397439 For n >= 2 the tail equals A005010 (9*2^n) reindexed; the doubling factor is A000079 (powers of 2).
%Y A397439 Cf. A003945 (g.f. (1+x)/(1-2*x)); here the numerator is squared, (1+x)^2/(1-2*x).
%Y A397439 Cf. A396406 (2D right-triangle reflection sequence, unequal legs).
%Y A397439 Cf. A397437 (4D analog) and A396927 (5D analog), same orthoscheme family.
%Y A397439 Cf. A008137 (3D all-equal-legs cube corner; affine Weyl group B~_3 growth series).
%K A397439 nonn,easy,new
%O A397439 0,2
